[2] Liberia: 1st Ebola death since July 2015
Date: Fri 4 Dec 2015
Source: The Oceanside Post [edited]
http://oceansidepost.com/2015/12/04/liberia-records-1st-ebola-death-since-july.html


Liberia said on [Mon 30 Nov 2015] that it had sought help from 2 experts from the US Centres for Disease Control and Prevention to determine the cause of the latest cases. The fatalities have been largely concentrated in Liberia, Sierra Leone, and Guinea -- Liberia alone has had more than 10 600 cases, and about 4800 people have died. The new Ebola cases in Liberia come less than a week after Guinea released its last patient and began the 42-day countdown to being declared Ebola-free... -- more

[See also: 3 Dec 2015 Liberia: last 2 Ebola patients recover, leave hospital
http://www.trust.org/item/20151203193032-4wnba/
After releasing the 2 known Ebola virus disease (EVD) cases from hospital on [Thu 3 Dec 2015], Liberia has started a new countdown to the World Health Organization (WHO) declaration of Liberia being free of the virus for a 3rd time, health officials said. According to Tolbert Nyenswah, head of Liberia's Ebola response "There are no cases in the ETUs (Ebola treatment units) in the entire Republic of Liberia," adding "EVD safety measures remain in place."

The 2 patients released from the Paynesville ETU are the father and younger brother of the presumed index case, a 15-year-old boy from a suburb of the capital Monrovia who died from the disease last week [week of 28 Nov 2015]. However, new cases could still emerge in Liberia since there are 165 contacts still under quarantine, of whom more than 30 are deemed high risk, health officials told Reuters.

Note: There have been reports of multiple breaches of EVD-prevention protocol, including the offices of Liberia's president, Ellen Johnson Sirleaf, and the Ministry of Justice (MOJ) failing to have "Ebola buckets" (buckets filled with water and chlorine) outside her offices) at the entry to their facilities... Reemergence of EVD cases in Liberia, possibly transmitted sexually by survivors, has called into question the current policy of declaring a country Ebola-free after 42 days.]

