[4] Prevention, research, funding
Prevention
----------
4 Dec 2015 Guinea-Bissau: awareness is the antidote to fear of Ebola
http://firstperson.oxfamamerica.org/2015/12/in-guinea-bissau-awareness-is-the-antidote-to-fear-of-ebola
["We've seen changes in people's habits. Now, many illnesses that used to come from the villages aren't appearing any more. I don't think people will forget that washing hands keeps their families healthy... Though the Ebola risks remain high, everyone I meet in the villages says NADEL [National Association for Local Development] and Femmes Travailleuses [National Commission of Women Workers] have helped them cope. A woman who lives in a community where [nurse] Cardoso works summed up the consensus: "Now, we have less fear of Ebola because we know what to do in order not to catch it."]

3 Dec 2015 Liberia: MoE mandates schools to reinstitute Ebola safety protocol
http://www.heritageliberia.net/heritagenews/index.php/2014-07-17-10-02-56/other-headlines/680-moe-mandates-schools-to-reinstitute-ebola-safety-protocol
[In response to the reemergence of Ebola virus disease in Liberia, on (Tue 1 Dec 2015), Liberia's Minister of Education, Romelle A Horton, directed Liberia's school administrators and teachers to reinstitute temperature-monitoring system teams and hand-washing stations at school entries "in full observance of the School Safety Protocol."
In addition, the ministry is calling on all parents, community leaders, civil society groups and other relevant stakeholders to support the implementation of the school Ebola safety protocols at homes and in communities.]

3 Dec 2015 Liberia: Students undergo regular temperature checks at Ebola victim's school
http://www.bushchicken.com/students-undergo-regular-temperature-checks-at-ebola-victims-school

4 Dec 2015 UK: Declining Ebola case numbers, new control methods prompt PHE screening scale-back
http://en.starafrica.com/news/declining-ebola-case-numbers-new-control-methods-prompt-phe-screening-scale-back.html
[Public Health England (PHE) is scaling down screening arrangements following a sustained decline in the Ebola outbreak in West Africa. Other factors influencing the decision include the introduction of new control methods such as a highly effective Ebola vaccination, the WHO declaring Sierra Leone Ebola transmission free and the continued low risk presented to the UK by the disease. Under the scaled back operations, from 5 Dec 2015 screening will stop for travellers from Sierra Leone, Guinea, and Liberia. PHE will maintain its monitoring system for high-risk returning workers until the outbreak has been declared over in the affected countries.]

3 Dec 2015 USA: ACLU-Yale report finds Ebola quarantines medically unjustified and unconstitutional
http://enewspf.com/2015/12/03/aclu-yale-report-finds-ebola-quarantines-medically-unjustified-and-unconstitutional/
[A report by the America Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) and the Yale Global Health Justice Partnership, issued 3 Dec 2015, recommends quarantine policies ensure future state responses to diseases are based on science, not politics.]
[But politicians had no choice but to respond "out of an abundance of caution" to the hysteria among the public in response to the news that the country was receiving large numbers of returning aid workers who had been exposed to Ebola patients. See also
4 Dec 2015 USA: Learning from Ebola: was quarantine too extreme a response?
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/04/insider/learning-from-ebola-was-quarantine-too-extreme-a-response.html
[A good discussion of the subject. - Mod.JW]

Research
--------
6 Dec 2015: Where does Ebola come from? Communicating science as a matter of life and death -- Part 1 of 2
http://blogs.plos.org/scicomm/2015/12/06/where-does-ebola-come-from-communicating-science-as-a-matter-of-life-and-death-part-1-of-2
[Posted by PLOS BLOGS in Public science communication. This is a long -- but very well written and worth reading -- simplification of the complex language used to describe fingerprinting (sequencing) of Ebola isolates to determine their origin. - Mod.JW]

Funding
-------
3 Dec 2015: New funding for Ebola hides an ongoing decline
http://medicalxpress.com/news/2015-12-funding-ebola-ongoing-decline.html
[A new report gives the 1st ever picture of global investment in Ebola research and development (R&D), reporting that this investment might have come at the expense of efforts to develop drugs, vaccines, and diagnostics for other neglected diseases, which collectively cause more than 6 million deaths every year in developing countries... -- more

3 Dec 2015 Liberia: 'UN Agencies, NGOs still withholding Ebola funds'
http://allafrica.com/stories/201512041083.html
[According to the former Minister of Health, Dr Walter T Gwenigale, who was the keynote speaker at the 1st Annual General & Scientific Meeting of the Liberia College of Physicians and Surgeons (LCPS), several United Nations agencies and international non-governmental organizations (NGOs) have not yet accounted for funds given to them to fight Ebola virus disease (EVD). Some of the funds have not yet been used, he stated. According to Dr Gwenigale, "All the money that was coming into this country during the Ebola period was not coming to the [Liberian] government. They were giving the funds to international NGOs, United Nations agencies, but people were coming to the government when other people were saying that the government got the money." Dr Gwenigale said the government must have a greater say in how funds are used whenever donors want to help the country, and is calling for a full accounting of the spent funds.]

[Compiled by: Celeste Whitlow <whitlow.celeste@gmail.com>]

